First, There must be suitable Laws for every occasion, and almost for every action that men do; for one Law cannot serve in all 
                     〈◊〉
                  , but every season and every action have their particular Laws attending thereupon for the preservation of right order: As for example;

But now if the Laws were few and short, and often read, it would prevent those Evils; 
                     〈◊〉
                   every one, knowing when they did well, and when ill, would be very cautious of their words and actions; and this would escape the Lawyers craft.
